Title: TranslateException uses `throw ex`, resetting the exception stack trace

Finding:
`TranslateException(Exception ex)` is a switch expression whose default arm is `_ => throw ex`. Because this is a separate method (not a `catch` block), `throw;` cannot be used, so the code uses `throw ex`, which re-throws but REPLACES the exception's original stack trace with the throw point inside TranslateException. Non-translated exceptions (e.g. InvalidOperationException, TimeoutException) propagate out of Execute/ExecuteAsync to ASP.NET's 500 handler with a degraded stack trace, making production debugging and logging harder. This is a well-known C# anti-pattern that analyzers flag. The intent (let non-file-system exceptions propagate unchanged while preserving their original origin) is better served by not catching them at all.

Fix instructions (follow exactly; make targeted, minimal changes):
In `Controllers/FilesController.cs`, eliminate the `throw ex` in `TranslateException` so non-translated exceptions propagate with their original stack trace. Move the type test into a `when` filter on the `catch` in both `Execute` and `ExecuteAsync` so only translated types are caught and everything else is never caught (preserving the stack trace for free). Concretely: in `Execute` change the catch to `catch (Exception ex) when (ex is ArgumentException or UnauthorizedAccessException or IOException) { return BadRequest(new { error = ex.Message }); }` and do the same in `ExecuteAsync`. Then delete the `TranslateException` method entirely (it is no longer needed) and update the XML doc comments on `Execute`/`ExecuteAsync` to note that the three root types (and their subtypes via inheritance, e.g. DirectoryNotFoundException/FileNotFoundException under IOException) are caught via the `when` filter and everything else propagates. Keep the existing FilesControllerTests passing; the `*_DoesNotSwallowUnhandledExceptions` and `Translate_PropagatesExceptionsOutsideTheTranslatedRoots` tests assert the same propagation behavior.

